Load Data

> data(CCS, package="BCA")

Create 50/50 Sample

> CCS$Sample <- create.samples(CCS, est = 0.50, val = 0.50, rand.seed = 1)
We created estimation and validation samples, much like we did in the logistic regression tutorial. The validation sample will later be used to evaluate the estimation model.

Create tree1CCS model

> tree1CCS <- rpart(MonthGive ~ AdultAge + Age20t29 + Age20t39 + Age60pls + 
+   Age80pls + Age70pls + AveDonAmt + AveIncEA + DonPerYear + DwelValEA + 
+   EngPrmLang + FinUnivP + hh1mem + hh1t2mem + LastDonAmt + NewDonor + Region + 
+   SomeUnivP + YearsGive, data=CCS, cp=0.01, subset=Sample == "Estimation")

This model uses all of the original variables from the CCS dataset with MonthGive as the target variable.

Plot of tree1CCS model without uniform branch distance

> rpart.plot(tree1CCS, type = 0, extra = 2, uniform = FALSE, fallen.leaves = 
+   TRUE)

This plot shows the best first split is on AveDonAmt at $12. Having branch length indicate the relative strength of relationships can be useful, but it can also make it difficult to read and interpret the plot.

Plot of tree1CCS model with uniform branch distance

> rpart.plot(tree1CCS, type = 0, extra = 2, uniform = TRUE, fallen.leaves = 
+   FALSE)

The uniform branch length makes reading labels a bit easier.

Model showing proportions

> rpart.plot(tree1CCS, type = 0, extra = 4, uniform = TRUE, fallen.leaves = 
+   FALSE)

This plot shows the proportions of the two values of the target variable at each leaf.

Create Log Variable

> CCS$Log.AveDonAmt <- with(CCS, log(AveDonAmt))
The use of this variable in the following models is to demonstrate that log transformations are not as beneficial for decision trees as they can be with logistic regression.

New model using log variable

> tree2CCS <- rpart(MonthGive ~ AdultAge + Age20t29 + Age20t39 + Age60pls + 
+   Age80pls + Age70pls  + AveIncEA + DonPerYear + DwelValEA + EngPrmLang + 
+   FinUnivP + hh1mem + hh1t2mem + LastDonAmt + NewDonor + Region + SomeUnivP + 
+   YearsGive + Log.AveDonAmt, data=CCS, cp=0.01, subset=Sample == "Estimation")

Plot of new model

> rpart.plot(tree2CCS, type = 0, extra = 2, uniform = TRUE, fallen.leaves = 
+   FALSE)

Delete Log Variable

> CCS <- within(CCS, {
+   Log.AveDonAmt <- NULL 
+ })
This variable is deleted because ultimately it produced a tree with the same members in the same groups as the non log-transformed model.

This model excludes AveDonAmt and as a result, LastDonAmt can now have a significant effect on the target variable. This is indicative that the two variables are correlated.

Plot of TreeNoADA

> rpart.plot(TreeNoADA, type = 0, extra = 2, uniform = TRUE, fallen.leaves = 
+   FALSE)

Full011 appears to be the best performing model in this case.
